Here there is something to note a,b = map(int, input().split()) why we had written this is if input is given in one single line, then input() stores it as a single sting "10  20". 
But now as we have to separate it so .split() method is used to separate the two strings as [ "10" , "20" ] . This .split() method saves by separating the string into 2 different candidates and also stores in a list.

Now why this map function is used ? : 
The map functions is --->
map(function, iterable)
function → what you want to apply
iterable → list / string / etc.

so at first when we put input() as 10, 20 then it is taken as a string. therefore we used split() function to split it into ["10" , "20"] . Now as they are still taken as string if we apply the operation then a+b will concatenate both to give as 1020, therefore the map function is used which applies the ,"int " function to both the splitted string 10 & 20 & int is applied to each element.
which makes them 
a = 10   # integer ✅  
b = 20 
Now the Operation will give answer which is actual meaning of operation rather than concatenation.
